            {
                "s2_paper_id": "d0b096421aea0ae569ecae0313f517c4fbd6b5c8",
                "title": "The Church, Authority, and Foucault: Imagining the Church as an Open Space of Freedom. By Steven G. Ogden. Routledge New Critical Thinking in Religion, Theology, and Biblical Studies. London: Routledge, 2017. x + 180 pp. $160.00 hardback; $28.98 e-book.",
                "year": 2018,
                "venue": "Church History: Studies in Christianity and Culture",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 0,
                "abstract": "internal conflicts among Catholics about the church\u2019s embrace of the social sciences. Here, the book falls short a bit in failing to offer a broader context for the internal Catholic debates of the era, namely the lack of interaction with non-Catholics; and the impact of the Modernist controversy that kept Catholics aloof from \u201cscientific\u201d reform, from the social sciences in general, and from any program of social engineering that was not directly controlled by the Catholic Church and its clergy. Though seen by fellow Catholics as \u201crevolutionary,\u201d Furfey\u2019s evolution in thought seems a natural consequence of his experiences and training. He was that rare priest who remembered that Catholic Action was a lay movement, and he supported psychology and the use of scientific data in promoting better society, without giving the final nod to the sole use of empirical data to resolve social problems. From the 1960s and up to his death in 1992 at 95, and consistent with his commitment to the Gospel\u2019s message of radical love and uplift of the poor, Furfey endorsed liberation theology, opposed the Vietnam War, and became a founding member of the International Committee of Conscience on Vietnam in 1973. Rademacher nicely sums up his career: \u201c. . . he sought to determine the proposed relationship between social scientific analysis, philosophy, theology, and spirituality and to put them into concrete application for the common good\u201d (8).",
